Sent: Fri, May 11, 2012 5:44 PM
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]
Subject: Rural outbreak of anthrax in San Luis


Bovine anthrax - Argentina (San Luis)
-------------------------------------
A mixed-breed herd of cattle in a cattle ranch 20 Kms from the provincial capital of San Luis suffered 4 acute deaths with extravasation of blood from natural orifices. A necropsy showed a moderate hepatitis and spenomegaly. A metatarsal bone was submitted to the laboratory for diagnosis and demonstrated _Bacillus anthracis_ slightly different morphologically from expected. Injected into white mice, they showed the normal clinical pattern of disease and died; _B. anthracis_ was recovered. The culture was sensitive to penicillin, tetracycline, phlofenicol, ampicillin, gentamycin, ciprofloxacin, and resistant to trimetroprim.

--
Ramon Noseda,
CFO-Director/Microbiologist,
Laboratorio Azul Diagnostico S.A.
Av. 25 de Mayo 479
(B 7300 FXE) Azul Bs. As.
Argentina
http://www.laboratorioazul.com.ar

[It is distinctly uncommon to have anthrax reported from San Luis. This is apparently the 1st in many years. Though it is not stated, the usual Argentine situation is for these affected herds to be unvaccinated.

San Luis is due west of Buenos Aires; see: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg
- Mod MHJ.]
